[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 is stable at 212. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 47 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
The Americas region reported 39 087 new cases (51.4% of the global newly reported cases) and 1722 deaths (43.8% of the global newly reported deaths). Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 74.8% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 8.7% and Peru at 5.6%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 34.2% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 22.2%, Canada at 15.6%, Mexico at 8.5%, Ecuador at 5.3% and Chile at 4.9%.

The European region reported 27 313 new cases (35.9% of the global newly reported cases) and 1904 deaths (48.4% of the global newly reported deaths). Russia reported 23.5% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 15.9%, France 13.7 7.9%, and Turkey 7.8%. Noteworthy is Belarus that reported 6.4% of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5305 new cases (7.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 157 deaths (4.0% of the global newly reported deaths). Saudi Arabia reported 1289 new cases representing 24.3% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran at 18.7%, Qatar 18.0%, Pakistan at 11.1%, and the United Arab Emirates at 9.2%. This is the 4rd consecutive day that Saudi Arabia has surpassed Iran.

The African region reported 769 new cases (1.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 16 deaths (0.41% of the global newly reported deaths). South Africa reported 32.1% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Algeria at 17.6%, Guinea at 9.0%, and Nigeria and Senegal each at 8.3%. Noteworthy is that 21 countries did not report any newly confirmed cases, including Ghana.

The Western Pacific region reported 1264 new cases (1.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 40 deaths (1.0% of the global newly reported deaths). Singapore reported 63.2% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 15.7%, and Japan at 15.1%. Given the high proportion of cases reported by Singapore, removing Singapore from the denominator, the Philippines represents 42.6% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan at 41.1% and Malaysia at 8.6%.

The South East Asia region reported 2288 new cases (3.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 93 deaths (2.4% of the global newly reported deaths). India reported 67.4% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 21.7% and Indonesia at 9.4%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 66.7% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 28.7%, and the Maldives 3.4%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region through (28 Apr 2020) at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend; the European region appears to have its cyclical weekend drop, lower than previous weekends and the rebound today (28 Apr 2020) is lower than pre-weekend reports. The America's region does not appear to have decreased even though there were 25 countries reporting no new cases in the past 24 hours.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
